Those who have not closed their buildings say they can protect their members by checking temperatures, sanitising sanctuaries and spacing worshippers six feet apart. And in at least eight states, stay-at-home orders do not apply to religious organisations - sometimes after legal battles. Some see a ban on church services as a violation of religious liberties guaranteed by the US constitution. Some services in the USA found inventive ways to make sure worshippers were still involved, while obeying social distancing. Mass at Our Lady of Sorrows Catholic Church in South Orange, New Jersey was streamed live, which parishioners' photos being placed on the seats. Daytona Beach Drive-in Christian Church in Florida saw worshippers follow the service from their cars. --BBC--